        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to obtain ALMA band 6 observations of CO(2-1) in the Ophiuchus cluster with a spatial resolution of 0.33 arc-seconds, well matched to our scheduled Chandra imaging. We do not require the additional ACA array. We will use only one pointing.

The line-of-sight velocity field of the H alpha gas suggests an offset from the BCG of order 600 km per second; the line widths in the ionised gas are on the order of a couple of hundred km per second. We therefore request the largest, 1875 MHz bandwidth (2507 km per second) for our observations. All base bands are FDM mode and dual polarisation. We propose to use the standard calibration.

Salome &amp; Combes (2003) find a strong correlation between the H alpha luminosity in a cool core system and the mass of cold molecular gas. Using their relation and the total H alpha luminosity in Ophiuchus, of 9e39 ergs/cm^2 extended over a 2 arc second region, we estimate the molecular gas mass to be 5e9 solar masses. We can use their equation 5 to convert this gas mass into an estimate of the integrated CO intensity. Using the standard N(H2) conversion factor, the 1.5 arc second beam size and a velocity width of 300 km/s, we estimate the integrated CO intensity to be 9.66 K. Conservatively assuming the mass is dispersed uniformly over the 1.5 arc seconds and scaling to a spatial resolution of 0.3 arc second we find a flux density of 0.39 K. To achieve a S/N or 5 we request 0.075 K rms with a velocity resolution of 30 km/s. Molecular gas typically traces the H alpha emission. In Ophiuchus the emission is strongly peaked in the central 0.5 arc second so we expect the majority of the emission to be detected at greater than 5 sigma.

We shall use spectral averaging of 4 to decrease the data rate.

The ALMA OT calculates the total observing time will all overheads to be 1.57 hours.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
